Innings break 2.05pm Alex Carey's late flourish gives Australia something to bowl at. They made a mess of an outstanding start. Aaron Finch and David Warner were superb up front on a difficult pitch but neither could kick on to a big score. Finch got out for exactly 100. Warner made 53 and then the side fell away from there.

Aaron Finch: "It would have been nice to go on with it. It's never ideal to get a hundred and then get out. There's still enough in the wicket though. That's a pretty good score. It wasn't the easiest wicket to start on, the ball was seaming. We were conscious to try and get through that with as little damage as possible and we were able to do that. We got ourselves into a decent position. We could have got a few more runs."

9.15am Good morning all, and welcome to the start of the World Cup proper. We've had a 31-match prologue - and jolly fun it has been too. But this is a proper heavyweight contest with proper grown-up consequences on the line. It's England v Australia, the World No.1s versus the serial World Cup champions, at the home of cricket no less. And there's a whole lot of jeopardy at stake too.

To the victor, the bragging rights, two precious points in the final push towards the semi-finals, and breathing room between themselves and the chasing pack - Sri Lanka, Pakistan and Bangladesh. To the loser, existential angst and the prospect of a squeaky closing week, with the unbeaten New Zealanders awaiting both teams, as well as India v England and Australia v South Africa (who will surely try to raise their game before skulking out of the back door)... sit tight, this one is unmissable!

9.40am So, what are we to make of the relative merits of these two teams? England, remember, have never won the World Cup. Australia are the defending champions and have hoovered up the trophy on a record five occasions. They know what it takes on the biggest stage ... as Jarrod Kimber points out in his telling analysis...

For England, Eoin Morgan is keeping his best poker-face in place, despite a massively dispiriting loss against Sri Lanka. There's no need to panic, he says...

Jofra Archer is fit to play," say the ECB. "Had a bowl through this morning. Precautionary. Felt some tightness in his left side." You can bet England wish they were in a position to rest him. No chance in a game this important ...

9.36am Alex Malcolm, who will be sharing the duties on the live commentary today, has been gleaning some intel on the likely Australia side.

"There was a whisper floating around yesterday that Lyon and Behrendorff were a huge chance to play," he says. "That was based on match ups. Lyon bowled beautifully to England in the warm-up game and sets up well for Morgan, Stokes, Moeen and has a superb record against Buttler in two games. The extra left-armer is again part match-up, part green track I think." And sure enough, it seems that Lyon has been marking out his run-up...

9.34am The suspicion from the sidelines is that England will be unchanged ... which means Mark Wood and Jofra Archer will be in harness once again, and James Vince will get another opportunity to partner Jonny Bairstow at the top of the order.

9.25am "Archer is fine," declares George Dobell, who has strolled onto the scene of the drama and done his best Red Adair impression. You'll never cut it in the tabloids, George ...

"Very heavy atmosphere," he adds, of the weather, presumably, rather than the vibe. "Like Sri Lanka, a bit. A win toss and bowl morning." I can vouch for the humidity levels in London this morning, the tube was like a sauna. And not one of those pleasant Finnish ones with an ice bath at the end of it.

9.22am Early drama at Lord's! Jofra Archer is having a fitness test! This is not good news for England at all. Their newest pace weapon has reportedly picked up a side problem ... and is being put through his paces as we speak. Will keep you posted...

9.15am Good morning all, and welcome to the start of the World Cup proper. We've had a 31-match prologue - and jolly fun it has been too. But this is a proper heavyweight contest with proper grown-up consequences on the line. It's England v Australia, the World No.1s versus the serial World Cup champions, at the home of cricket no less. And there's a whole lot of jeopardy at stake too.

To the victor, the bragging rights, two precious points in the final push towards the semi-finals, and breathing room between themselves and the chasing pack - Sri Lanka, Pakistan and Bangladesh. To the loser, existential angst and the prospect of a squeaky closing week, with the unbeaten New Zealanders awaiting both teams, as well as India v England and Australia v South Africa (who will surely try to raise their game before skulking out of the back door)... sit tight, this one is unmissable!
